# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The site was previously occupied by a mansion known as Alder Hey which the local poor law guardians acquired for use as a children's home in 1910.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The mansion was converted for use as a military hospital in 1914.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the First World War, the United States Army established Camp Hospital 40 on the site, operated by Hospital Unit Q and, subsequently, Unit W.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] American sources commonly refer to Alder Hey as being within Liverpool's Knotty Ash area.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the Second World War, parts of the hospital were again used to treat injured military personnel.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The Liverpool Neonatal Surgical Unit opened at the hospital in 1953.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] This unit was the first neonatal intensive care unit in the United Kingdom.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The opening was largely due to the efforts of Isabella Forshall, a paediatric surgeon.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1990 when Myrtle Street Children's Hospital (founded in 1869 and previously known as Royal Liverpool Children's Hospital) closed, Alder Hey absorbed its A&E department.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital authority was one of 57 such bodies which became an NHS hospital trust in 1991.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Ronald McDonald House, a home for the families of sick children, opened in 1993.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1999 an inquiry was instituted into the Alder Hey organs scandal and to investigate the hospital's practices in respect of removal and retention of human tissue.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The inquiry had far-reaching effects throughout the UK hospital system and provided the impetus for the Human Tissue Act 2004.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In August 2008 the Royal Liverpool Children's NHS Trust became an NHS foundation trust and changed its name to Alder Hey NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Between 2010 and 2014 the number of doctors employed at the trust increased from 269 to 344, while the number of managers increased from 70 to 86.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] At the end of March 2017, the trust was confirmed as one of four additional NHS Global Digital Exemplars, joining the twelve announced in September 2016.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey had its centenary year in 2014, the last year in which it operated from the buildings on its original site.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A new hospital was procured under Private Finance Initiative contract in neighbouring Springfield Park.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The works, which were carried out by Laing O'Rourke at a cost of £187 million, began on 26 March 2013 and the hospital opened in October 2015.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It was Europe's first children's hospital built in a park.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The original Alder Hey buildings were mostly demolished and the land was reclaimed as new parkland for the surrounding community.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Features of the new hospital include access to play areas, natural light and striking views of the park are available wherever possible Children and young people were involved with the design of the new hospital.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A drawing of a flower by teenage patient Eleanor Brogan impressed architects and inspired their final design.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is a centre of excellence for oncology and muscular dystrophy as well as spinal, heart and brain conditions.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey has Europe's first 3T Intraoperative MRI scanner which is a pioneering technology for neurosurgery, providing surgeons with extremely high resolution images and reducing the need for repeat operations in 90% of cases.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It currently employs about 2,400 staff and treats over 270,000 children from across the UK each year.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts paediatric research into children's medicines, infection, inflammation and oncology.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It has research partners including the University of Liverpool and is a member of Liverpool Health Partners.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts more than 100 clinical research studies on an ongoing basis, ranging from observation to clinical trials.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is within the National Institute for Health and Care Research's Top 100 Performing Trust's for participation recruitment in 2013/14.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey was a finalist in the Clinical Research Impact category of the 2013 HSJ Awards and in 2014 the innovation team received the Health Service Journal Award for improving health care with technology.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2016 the first phase of a bespoke research, education and innovation centre, Institute in the Park, opened next to Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In November 2015, the institute hosted a children's health Hackathon in conjunction with Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey Children's Charity supports the work of the hospital.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In addition to NHS funding which covers the running costs of the hospital, Alder Hey relies on charitable support.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Funds are spent directly on initiatives in the hospital to benefit patients.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It funds research initiatives, patient and family enhancements and state of the art medical equipment.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Known as the 'Imagine Appeal' until 2012, Alder Hey Children's Charity is based within the hospital.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 14 October 2013 the charity launched a public appeal to raise £30m to fund equipment, facilities and research at Alder Hey's new hospital, Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2015 the charity announced over £20m had been raised.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2009 charitable support allowed Alder Hey to buy Europe's first 3T intraoperative MRI scanner.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In one charitably funded project, the sound recordist and musician Chris Watson was employed to devise an art project, using bird song recordings made by children to calm other young patients as they received injections and other treatments.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1978, the charity Art For Their Sake, a team of volunteer artists led by founder George Nicholas (now of Ormskirk, England), produced the world's longest mural in the corridors of Alder Hey Children's Hospital.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A Guinness Record was set with a total of 17,963 square feet of murals, and awarded to the hospital in 1986.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Nicholas and his team continued to work on these murals for a period of 30 years, adding to as well as restoring and maintaining, for a total of over 34,000 square feet.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey runs an Arts for Health programme, funded entirely through charitable sources including Alder Hey Children's Charity.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme aims to enhance the experience of being a patient and includes animation projects, music and dance therapy, creative writing, comedy workshops and storytelling.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] An international child health development programme led by Alder Hey clinicians focuses on humanitarian work in developing countries.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme includes provision of immediate medical support, knowledge sharing and involvement with international clinical trials.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme has undertaken work across Africa and Asia, including Pakistan, Malawi, Nepal and India.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the 1990s, Alder Hey was featured in the BBC television series *Children's Hospital*.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2011, chef Heston Blumenthal took to the challenge of changing the dinner menu of Alder Hey Children's Hospital on his televised show, *Heston's Mission Impossible*.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Since September 2012, Alder Hey has regularly featured on the CBBC television series *Operation Ouch!*.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2013, the Care Quality Commission's Intelligent Monitoring system placed Alder Hey in category one, meaning it would be amongst the first hospitals to be inspected under a new style of inspection.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In May 2014, Alder Hey was inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Requires Improvement.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In June 2015, Alder Hey was re-inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Good, and was rated Outstanding in the Caring category.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Another inspection took place in 2018, the overall rating was unchanged.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Dame Josephine Williams was appointed Chair of the Trust Board in February 2019.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Louise Shepherd CBE was appointed Chief Executive of the trust in March 2008.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 26 January 2023, the Alder Hey Children's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust was granted the Honorary Freedom of the Metropolitan Borough of Sefton.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The hospital was founded by Thomas Pretious Heslop as the *Birmingham and Midland Free Hospital for Sick Children* at 138–9 Steelhouse Lane in 1862.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] It moved to a new site on Ladywood Middleway in 1917.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In March 1986, a charity concert was held called "Heart Beat 86" at the nearby National Exhibition Centre, featuring George Harrison, which raised money for the hospital.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In October 1998 the hospital returned to Steelhouse Lane, to the buildings previously used by the Birmingham General Hospital, as the Diana, Princess of Wales Children's Hospital – in honour of Diana, Princess of Wales, who had died the year before.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The opening ceremony was carried out by the Queen.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 2007, a new extension designed by RPS Group was opened.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The extension created a burns unit, one of three such centres of excellence in the country.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] As well as this, it established an outpatients department, a neonatal ward, a burns operating theatre, as well as additional classrooms for the Education Centre, allowing children to continue their education whilst undergoing medium to long-term care in the hospital.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The trust led a consortium of organisations called **Forward Thinking Birmingham** commissioned to provide mental health services for young people in the city up to the age of 25 from April 2016.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] Services for adults were previously provided by Birmingham and Solihull Mental Health NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 1970, surgeons completed the first separation of conjoined twins at the hospital.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The hospital was managed by the Birmingham Children's Hospital NHS Trust until 2017 when it merged with the Women's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust to create the Birmingham Women's and Children's NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The trust was named by the *Health Service Journal* as one of the top hundred NHS trusts to work for in 2015.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] At that time it had 3236 full-time equivalent staff and a sickness absence rate of 3.39%.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] 89% of staff recommend it as a place for treatment and 74% recommended it as a place to work.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] The Trust's Professor Anita Macdonald, Consultant Paediatric Dietitian was awarded an OBE for services to Dietetics in the Queen's Birthday Honours 2015.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/birmingham-children-s-hospital] In 2016, it became the first children's hospital to be rated Outstanding by the Care Quality Commission.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The hospital has its origins in the **Hospital for Sick Children** on St Michael's Hill founded in 1866.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The initial building was a large converted dwelling house on Royal Fort Road, south of the Royal Fort gatehouse, with accommodation for 40 patients.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] One of the hospital's first salaried doctors was the pioneering female surgeon, Eliza Walker, appointed as House Surgeon in 1873.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] A much expanded hospital was built nearby to the designs of Robert Carwen in the Tudor gothic revival style in 1885.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Only the entrance building fronting on to St Michael's Hill now survives.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The hospital was later renamed as the **Bristol Royal Hospital for Sick Children**.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The new Children's Hospital opened on 22 April 2001, replacing the old children's hospital on St Michael's Hill, at a cost £30 million.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] One of the main aims of the design, in addition to providing the most up-to-date facilities possible, was to overcome many of the difficulties that face patients, families and staff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In February 2014, it was agreed an inquiry would be held into the Bristol heart scandal, following heart surgery deaths at the hospital.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The inquiry published a report in June 2016, saying that “parents had been let down”.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] An extension was built to accommodate services moved from Frenchay Hospital in 2014, including neuroscience, scoliosis surgery, burns and plastic surgery, bringing all inpatient children's services in Bristol to one location.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In 2015, a neuro-rehabilitation unit was built to support the moved services.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In May 2014, a new helipad on the roof of the neighbouring Bristol Royal Infirmary became fully operational and will receive air ambulances from Bristol and the surrounding area, which will speed up transfer times for patients who are air lifted to the hospital.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The HELP Appeal supported the construction of the helipad with a grant of £500,000.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Wallace & Gromit's Grand Appeal is the only charity that fundraises exclusively for the hospital and the neonatal intensive care unit at St Michael's Hospital, to provide facilities and comforts for patients and their families.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The Grand Appeal raised £12M towards the new building for the child-friendly hospital, which opened in April 2001.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Sculptures were decorated by a range of artists and celebrities, including Joanna Lumley, Sir Peter Blake, Cath Kidston and Jools Holland.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] At the end of the art trail, each sculpture was auctioned to raise funds for Bristol Children's Hospital.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] The Grand Appeal has pledged to raise £3.5M for equipment for Bristol Children's Hospital, including a state of the art CT Scanner, an intraoperative MRI scanner, family facilities and child-friendly artwork to help save the lives of sick children at the hospital.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] All funds raised by Gromit Unleashed will contribute towards this.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Bristol & Weston Hospitals Charity (BWHC) raises around £2M for all ten hospitals in the trust.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] It provides equipment, ward refurbishments and additional extras.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] It was formerly known as Above & Beyond and has existed since 1974.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In 2013, the charity's Golden Gift Appeal raised £6M.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] In 1997, arts consultant, Lesley Greene, was commissioned to develop an arts strategy for the new hospital.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] This project was committed to integrated designs, a commitment to consultation and the family.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Her active research programme led to the appointment of lead artist, Ray Smith, Eva Elsner, and Annie Lovejoy who contributed to the planning of the commissions programme.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Artworks were commissioned from more than twenty artists, many of which were site specific.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] These commissions were funded by the hospital's own fundraising arm, The Wallace and Gromit Grand Appeal.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] Records of the Bristol Royal Hospital for Children are held at Bristol Archives (Ref.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/bristol-royal-hospital-for-children] 37424) (online catalogue) and School of Nursing records (Ref.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-and-vale-university-health-board] The Board supports a population of around 445,000 people living in Cardiff and the Vale of Glamorgan.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-and-vale-university-health-board] It oversees seventeen health centres, public health and community care services and also has a range of specialist services used by the whole of Wales, including renal, paediatric, neurology and bone marrow transplantation.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-and-vale-university-health-board] As of June 2020, Charles Janczewski is the chairman of the Board.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-and-vale-university-health-board] The board is one of the first organisations in the UK to make wifi available in its hospitals, on the basis that enables patients to stay in touch with their family and friends, and improves the way it interacts with patients.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-and-vale-university-health-board] It was reported that there had been 3,609 recorded staff complaints about staffing levels between 2012 and 2015.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-and-vale-university-health-board] A review published in July 2015 found the emergency department was "significantly under-staffed" and had a poor skill mix, particularly in the paediatric department.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff is the main commercial centre of Wales as well as the base for the Senedd, the Welsh Parliament.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] At the 2021 census, the unitary authority area population was put at 362,400, an increase of 4.7% compared to the 2011 census when the population was 346,100.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The population of the wider urban area in 2011 was 479,000.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In 2011, it ranked sixth in the world in a *National Geographic* magazine list of alternative tourist destinations.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] It is the most popular destination in Wales with 21.3 million visitors in 2017.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] It was voted as the best city in the UK in the 2023 Readers' Choice Awards.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff is a major centre for television and film production (such as the 2005 revival of *Doctor Who*, *Torchwood* and *Sherlock*) and is the Welsh base for the main national broadcasters.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff Bay contains the Senedd building and the Wales Millennium Centre arts complex.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Work continues at Cardiff Bay and in the centre on projects such as Cardiff International Sports Village, BBC drama village, and a new business district.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The anglicised *Cardiff* is derived from *Caerdyf*, with the Welsh *f* [v] borrowed as *ff* /f/, as also happens in *Taff* (from Welsh *Taf*) and *Llandaff* (from Welsh *Llandaf*).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The antiquarian William Camden (1551–1623) suggested that the name Cardiff may derive from **Caer-Didi* ("the Fort of Didius"), a name supposedly given in honour of Aulus Didius Gallus, governor of a nearby province at the time when the Roman fort was established.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Although some sources repeat this theory, it has been rejected on linguistic grounds by modern scholars such as Professor Gwynedd Pierce.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Archaeological evidence from sites in and around Cardiff show that people had settled in the area by at least around 6000 BC, during the early Neolithic: about 1,500 years before either Stonehenge or the Great Pyramid of Giza was completed.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] These include the St Lythans burial chamber near Wenvoe, (approximately four miles or six km west of Cardiff city centre); the Tinkinswood burial chamber, near St.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Nicholas (about six miles or ten km west of Cardiff city centre), the Cae'rarfau Chambered Tomb, Creigiau (about six miles or ten km northwest of Cardiff city centre) and the Gwern y Cleppa long barrow, near Coedkernew, Newport (about eight miles or thirteen km northeast of Cardiff city centre).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] A group of five Bronze Age tumuli is at the summit of the Garth, within the county's northern boundary.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Four Iron Age hill fort and enclosure sites have been identified within Cardiff's county boundaries, including Caerau Hillfort, an enclosed area of 5.1 hectares (12+1⁄2 acres).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Until the Roman conquest of Britain, Cardiff was part of the territory of the Silures – a Celtic British tribe that flourished in the Iron Age – whose territory included the areas that would become known as Breconshire, Monmouthshire and Glamorgan.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The 3.2 ha (8-acre) fort established by the Romans near the mouth of the River Taff in AD 75, in what would become the north western boundary of the centre of Cardiff, was built over an extensive settlement that had been established by the Romans in the 50s AD.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The fort was one of a series of military outposts associated with *Isca Augusta* (Caerleon) that acted as border defences.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The fort may have been abandoned in the early 2nd century as the area had been subdued.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] However, by this time a civilian settlement, or *vicus*, was established.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] It was likely made up of traders who made a living from the fort, ex-soldiers and their families.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] A Roman villa has been discovered at Ely.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Contemporary with the Saxon Shore forts of the 3rd and 4th centuries, a stone fortress was established at Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Similar to the shore forts, the fortress was built to protect Britannia from raiders.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Coins from the reign of Gratian indicate that Cardiff was inhabited until at least the 4th century; the fort was abandoned towards the end of the 4th century, as the last Roman legions left the province of Britannia with Magnus Maximus.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Little is known of the fort and civilian settlement in the period between the Roman departure from Britain and the Norman Conquest.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The settlement probably shrank in size and may even have been abandoned.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In the absence of Roman rule, Wales was divided into small kingdoms; early on, Meurig ap Tewdrig emerged as the local king in Glywysing (which later became Glamorgan).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The area passed through his family until the advent of the Normans in the 11th century.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In 1081 William I, King of England visited Cardiff as part of an armed pilgrimage across South Wales and ordered work to begin on the castle keep within the walls of the old Roman fort.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff Castle has been at the heart of the city ever since.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The castle was substantially altered and extended during the Victorian period by John Crichton-Stuart, 3rd Marquess of Bute, and the architect William Burges.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Original Roman work can, however, still be distinguished in the wall facings.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] A town grew up under the castle, consisting mainly of settlers from England.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff had a population of between 1,500 and 2,000 in the Middle Ages – a normal size for a Welsh town in the period.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] It was the centre of the Norman Marcher Lordship of Glamorgan.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] By the end of the 13th century, Cardiff was the only town in Wales with a population exceeding 2,000, although it remained relatively small compared with notable towns in England and continued to be contained within its walls, which were begun as a wooden palisade in the early 12th century.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] It was of sufficient size and importance to receive a series of charters, notably in 1331 from William La Zouche, Lord of Glamorgan through marriage with the de Clare family, Edward III in 1359, then Henry IV in 1400, and later Henry VI.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In 1404, Owain Glyndŵr burned Cardiff and took possession of the Castle.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] As many of the buildings were made of timber and tightly packed within the town walls, much of Cardiff was destroyed.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The settlement was soon rebuilt on the same street plan and began to flourish again.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In 1536, the Laws in Wales Acts 1535–1542 led to the creation of Glamorganshire and Cardiff was made the county town, it also became part of Kibbor hundred, around the same time the Herberts became the most powerful family in the area.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In 1538, Henry VIII closed Cardiff's Dominican and Franciscan friaries, whose remains were used as building materials.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff became a borough in 1542 and further Royal Charters were granted to it by Elizabeth I in 1600 and James I in 1608.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In 1573, it was made a head port for collection of customs duties.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Pembrokeshire historian George Owen described Cardiff in 1602 as "the fayrest towne in Wales yett not the welthiest".
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] It gained a second Royal Charter in 1608.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] A disastrous flood in the Bristol Channel on 30 January 1607 (now believed to have been a tidal wave) changed the course of the River Taff and ruined St Mary's Parish Church, which was replaced by a chapel of ease dedicated to St John the Baptist.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] During the Second English Civil War St Fagans, just to the west of the town, the Battle of St Fagans, between Royalist rebels and a New Model Army detachment, was a decisive victory for the Parliamentarians that allowed Oliver Cromwell to conquer Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] It was the last major battle in Wales, with about 200, mostly Royalist soldiers killed.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff was at peace throughout the ensuing century.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In 1766, John Stuart, 1st Marquess of Bute married into the Herbert family and was later created Baron Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In 1778, he began renovating Cardiff Castle.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] A racecourse, printing press, bank and coffee house opened in the 1790s and Cardiff gained a stagecoach service to London.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Despite these improvements, Cardiff's position in the Welsh urban hierarchy declined over the 18th century.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Iolo Morganwg called it "an obscure and inconsiderable place" and the 1801 census found a population of only 1,870, making it only the 25th largest town in Wales, well behind Merthyr and Swansea.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In 1793, John Crichton-Stuart, 2nd Marquess of Bute was born.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] He spent his life building the Cardiff docks and was later hailed as "the creator of modern Cardiff".
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] A twice-weekly boat service between Cardiff and Bristol opened in 1815, and in 1821, the Cardiff Gas Works was established.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] After the Napoleonic Wars Cardiff suffered some social and industrial unrest, starting with the trial and hanging of Dic Penderyn in 1831.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The town grew rapidly from the 1830s onwards, when the Marquess of Bute built a dock, which eventually linked to the Taff Vale Railway.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff became the main port for coal exports from the Cynon, Rhondda, and Rhymney valleys, and grew in population at a rate of nearly 80 per cent per decade between 1840 and 1870.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Much of this was due to migration from within and outside Wales: in 1841, a quarter of Cardiff's population were English-born and more than 10 per cent born in Ireland.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] By the 1881 census, Cardiff had overtaken Merthyr and Swansea to become the largest town in Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff's status as the premier town in South Wales was confirmed when it was chosen as the site for the University College of South Wales and Monmouthshire in 1883.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] A permanent military presence was established with the completion of Maindy Barracks in 1877.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff faced a challenge in the 1880s when David Davies of Llandinam and the Barry Railway Company promoted rival docks at Barry.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] These had the advantage of being accessible in all tides: David Davies claimed his venture would cause "grass to grow in the streets of Cardiff".
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] From 1901 coal exports from Barry surpassed those from Cardiff, but the administration of the coal trade remained centred on Cardiff, in particular its Coal Exchange, where the price of coal on the British market was determined and the first million-pound deal was struck in 1907.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The city also strengthened its industrial base when the owners of the Dowlais Ironworks in Merthyr (who would later form part of Guest, Keen and Nettlefolds) built a steelworks close to the docks at East Moors, which Lord Bute opened on 4 February 1891.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff became a county borough on 1 April 1889 under the Local Government Act 1888.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The town had grown rapidly and had a population of over 123,000.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] It retained its county borough status until 1974.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] King Edward VII granted Cardiff city status on 28 October 1905.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] It acquired a Roman Catholic cathedral in 1916.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Following a brief post-war boom, Cardiff docks entered a prolonged decline in the interwar period.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] By 1936, trade was at less than half its value in 1913, reflecting the slump in demand for Welsh coal.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Bomb damage in the Cardiff Blitz of World War II included the devastation of Llandaff Cathedral, and in the immediate postwar years, the city's link with the Bute family came to an end.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The city was recognised as the capital city of Wales on 20 December 1955, in a written reply by the Home Secretary, Gwilym Lloyd George.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Welsh local authorities had been divided: only 76 out of 161 chose Cardiff in a 1924 poll organised by the *South Wales Daily News*.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The subject was not debated again until 1950, and meanwhile Cardiff took steps to promote its "Welshness".
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The stalemate between Cardiff and cities such as Caernarfon and Aberystwyth was not broken until Cardiganshire County Council decided to support Cardiff; and in a new local authority vote, 134 out of 161 voted for Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff therefore celebrated two important anniversaries in 2005.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The East Moors Steelworks closed in 1978 and Cardiff lost population in the 1980s, consistent with a wider pattern of counter-urbanisation in Britain.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] However, it recovered to become one of the few cities outside London where population grew in the 1990s.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The relative lack of local support for the Assembly and difficulties between the Welsh Office and Cardiff Council in acquiring the originally preferred venue, Cardiff City Hall, encouraged other local authorities to bid to house the Assembly.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] However, the Assembly was eventually located at Tŷ Hywel in Cardiff Bay in 1999.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In 2005, a new debating chamber on an adjacent site, designed by Richard Rogers, was opened.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The Senedd (Welsh Parliament; Welsh: *Senedd Cymru*) has been based in Cardiff Bay since its formation in 1999 as the "National Assembly for Wales".
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The Senedd building was opened on 1 March 2006 by The Queen.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The Members of the Senedd (MSs), the Senedd Commission and ministerial support staff are based in Cardiff Bay.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff is represented by twelve MSs in two constituencies; Caerdydd Ffynnon Taf and Caerdydd Penarth.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] These constituencies for the Senedd are formed by pairing up the Westminster constituencies.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Each constituency returns six members to the Senedd.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The most recent Senedd election was held on 7 May 2026.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Caerdydd Ffynnon Taf is represented by Zaynub Akbar (Plaid Cymru), Nick Carter (Plaid Cymru), Dafydd Trystan Davies (Plaid Cymru), Cai Parry-Jones (Reform UK), Shav Taj (Welsh Labour) and Paul Rock (Wales Green Party).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Caerdydd Penarth is represented by Anna Brychan (Plaid Cymru), Leticia Gonzalez (Plaid Cymru), Kiera Marshall (Plaid Cymru), Joseph Martin (Reform UK), Anthony Slaughter (Wales Green Party) and Huw Thomas (Welsh Labour).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] At Westminster, Cardiff is represented by four constituencies: Cardiff East, Cardiff North, Cardiff South and Penarth, and Cardiff West.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The Welsh Government is headquartered in Cardiff's Cathays Park, where most of its civil servants are based, with smaller numbers in other central locations: Cathays, Canton, and Cardiff Bay.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] There are other Welsh Government offices in other parts of Wales, such as Llandudno and Aberystwyth, and there are international offices.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] is home to some of the Council's departments and Council Chambers.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Between 1889 and 1974 Cardiff was a county borough governed by Cardiff County Borough Council (known as Cardiff City Council after 1905).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Between 1974 and 1996, Cardiff was governed by Cardiff City Council, a district council of South Glamorgan.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Since local government reorganisation in 1996, Cardiff has been governed by the City and County Council of Cardiff, based at County Hall in Atlantic Wharf, Cardiff Bay.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Voters elect 75 councillors every four years.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Between the 2004 and 2012 local elections, no individual political party held a majority on Cardiff County Council.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The Liberal Democrats held the largest number of seats and Cllr Rodney Berman was Leader of the council.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The Liberal Democrats and Plaid Cymru formed a partnership administration.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In the 2012 elections the Labour Party achieved an outright majority, after gaining an additional 33 seats across the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff is divided into communities, several with their own community council and the rest governed directly by Cardiff City Council.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The last contested elections would have been held at the same time as the 2017 Cardiff Council election had there been more candidates standing than available seats.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The centre of Cardiff is relatively flat and bounded by hills to the east, north and west.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Its location influenced its development as the world's largest coal port, notably its proximity and easy access to the coalfields of the South Wales Valleys.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The highest point in the local authority area is Garth Hill, 307 m (1,007 ft) above sea level.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff is built on reclaimed marshland on a bed of Triassic stones.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] This reclaimed marshland stretches from Chepstow to the Ely Estuary, which is the natural boundary of Cardiff and the Vale of Glamorgan.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Triassic landscapes of this part of the world are usually shallow and low-lying, consistent with the flatness of the centre of Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The classic Triassic marl, sand and conglomerate rocks are used predominantly throughout Cardiff as building materials.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Many of these Triassic rocks are purplish, especially the coastal marl found near Penarth.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] One of the Triassic rocks used in Cardiff is "Radyr Stone", a freestone which as its name suggests is quarried in the Radyr district.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff has also imported some materials for buildings: Devonian sandstones (the Old Red Sandstone) from the Brecon Beacons has been used.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Most famously, the buildings of Cathays Park, the civic centre in the centre of the city, are built of Portland stone from Dorset.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] A widely used building stone in Cardiff is the yellow-grey Liassic limestone rock of the Vale of Glamorgan, including the rare "Sutton Stone", a conglomerate of lias limestone and carboniferous limestone.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff is bordered to the west by the rural district of the Vale of Glamorgan, also known as the Garden of Cardiff, to the east by the city of Newport; to the north by the South Wales Valleys, and to the south by the Severn Estuary and Bristol Channel.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The River Taff winds through the city centre and together with the River Ely flows into the freshwater Cardiff Bay.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] A third river, the Rhymney, flows through the east of the city directly into the Severn Estuary.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff lies near the Glamorgan Heritage Coast, stretching westward from Penarth and Barry – commuter towns of Cardiff – with striped yellow-blue Jurassic limestone cliffs.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The Glamorgan coast is the only part of the Celtic Sea with exposed Jurassic (blue lias) geology.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] This stretch of coast with its reefs, sandbanks and serrated cliffs was a ship graveyard; many ships sailing to Cardiff during the industrial era were wrecked on this hostile coastline during west/south-westerly gales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Smuggling, deliberate shipwrecking and attacks on ships were also common.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] "Inner Cardiff" consists of the wards of Plasnewydd, Gabalfa, Roath, Cathays, Adamsdown and Splott ward on the north and east of the city centre, and Butetown, Grangetown, Riverside and Canton to the south and west.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The inner-city areas to the south of the A4161 road, known as the "Southern Arc", are with the exception of Cardiff Bay some of the poorest districts of Wales, with low levels of economic activity.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] On the other hand, Gabalfa, Plasnewydd and Cathays north of the 'arc' have large student populations, and Pontcanna (north of Riverside and alongside Canton) is a favourite for students and young professionals.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Penylan, to the north east of Roath Park, is an affluent area popular with older parents and the retired.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] To the west lie Ely and Caerau, which have some of the largest housing estates in the United Kingdom.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] With the exception of some outlying privately built estates at Michaelston-super-Ely, this is an economically disadvantaged area with high numbers of unemployed households.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Culverhouse Cross is a more affluent western area of the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Fairwater, Heath, Birchgrove, Gabalfa, Mynachdy, Llandaff North, Llandaff, Llanishen, Radyr, Whitchurch & Tongwynlais, Rhiwbina, Thornhill, Lisvane and Cyncoed lie in an arc from the north-west to the north-east of the centre.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Lisvane, Cyncoed, Radyr and Rhiwbina contain some of the most expensive housing in Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Further east lie the wards of Pontprennau and Old St Mellons, St Mellons, Rumney, Pentwyn, Llanrumney, Llanedeyrn and Trowbridge.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The last four are largely public housing stock, although much new private housing is being built in Trowbridge.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Pontprennau is the newest "suburb" of Cardiff, while Old St Mellons has a history going back to the 11th-century Norman Conquest.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The region that may be called "Rural Cardiff" contains the villages of St Fagans, Creigiau, Pentyrch, Tongwynlais and Gwaelod-y-garth.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In 2017, plans were approved for a new suburb of 7,000 homes between Radyr and St Fagans, known as Plasdŵr.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] St Fagans, home to the Museum of Welsh Life, is protected from further development.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Since 2000, there has been a marked change of scale and building height in Cardiff, with the development of the city centre's first purpose-built high-rise apartments.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Tall buildings have been built in the city centre and Cardiff Bay, and more are planned.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff, in the north temperate zone, has a maritime climate (Köppen: Cfb) marked by mild weather that is often cloudy, wet and windy.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff is one of the warmest and wettest cities in the UK, with an average annual temperature and rainfall of approximately 11°C and 1200mm respectively.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Summers tend to be warm and sunny, with average maxima between 19 and 22 °C (66 and 72 °F).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Winters are fairly wet, but excessive rainfall as well as frost are rare.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Spring and autumn feel similar, with mild temperatures averaging around 15°C as daytime maxima.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Rain is unpredictable at any time of year, although showers tend to be shorter in summer.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The northern part of the county, being higher and inland, tends to be cooler and wetter than the city centre.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff's maximum and minimum monthly temperatures average 21.8 °C (71.2 °F) (July) and 2.5 °C (36.5 °F) (January and February).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff has 1,573 hours of sunshine in an average year (Wales 1,407.5 hours).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff is sunniest in July, with an average 199.6 hours during the month (Wales 177 hours), and least sunny in December with 50.4 hours (Wales 41.4 hours).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff experiences less rainfall than average for Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] It falls on 153 days in an average year, with total annual rainfall of 1,203.3 mm (47.37 in).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Following a period of decline in the 1970s and 1980s, Cardiff's population is growing again.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Between mid-2007 and mid-2008, Cardiff was the fastest-growing local authority in Wales, with growth of 1.2%.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] According to 2001 census data, Cardiff was the 21st largest urban area in the United Kingdom.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The Cardiff Larger Urban Zone (a Eurostat definition including the Vale of Glamorgan and a number of local authorities in the Valleys) has 841,600 people, the 10th largest LUZ in the UK.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The Cardiff and South Wales Valleys metropolitan area has a population of nearly 1.1 million.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Official census estimates of the city's total population have been disputed.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The city council published two articles arguing that the 2001 census seriously under-reported the population of Cardiff, and in particular the ethnic minority population of some inner city areas.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The Welsh Government's official mid-year estimate of the population of the Cardiff local authority area in 2019 was 366,903.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] At the 2011 census, the official population of the Cardiff Built Up Area (BUA) was put at 447,287.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The BUA is not contiguous with the local authority boundary and aggregates data at a lower level; for Cardiff this includes the urban part of Cardiff, Penarth/Dinas Powys, Caerphilly and Pontypridd.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff has an ethnically diverse population due to past trading connections, post-war immigration and large numbers of foreign students who attend university in the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The ethnic make-up of Cardiff's population at the 2011 census was: 84.7% White, 1.6% mixed White and Black African/Caribbean, 0.7% mixed White and Asian, 0.6% mixed other, 8.1% Asian, 2.4% Black, 1.4% Arab and 0.6% other ethnic groups.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] This means almost 53,000 people from a non-white ethnic group reside in the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] This diversity, especially that of the city's long-established African and Arab communities, has been recorded in cultural exhibitions and events, along with books published on this subject.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] There are seven NHS hospitals in the city, the largest being the University Hospital of Wales, which is the third largest hospital in the UK and deals with most accidents and emergencies.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The University Dental Hospital, which provides emergency treatment, is also located on this site.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Llandough Hospital is located in the south of the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] David's Hospital, the city's newest hospital, built behind the former building, is located in Canton and provides services for the elderly and children.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff Royal Infirmary is on Newport Road, near the city centre.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The majority of this hospital was closed in 1999, but the west wing remained open for clinic services, genitourinary medicine and rehabilitation treatment.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Rookwood Hospital and the Velindre Cancer Centre are also located within Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] They are administered by the Cardiff and Vale University Health Board, with the exception of Velindre, which is run by a separate trust.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Spire Healthcare, a private hospital, is in Pontprennau.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff has a chequered linguistic history with Welsh, English, Latin, Norse and Norman French preponderant at different times.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Welsh was the majority language in Cardiff from the 13th century until the city's explosive growth in the Victorian era.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] As late as 1850, five of the 12 Anglican churches within the current city boundaries conducted their services exclusively in Welsh, while only two worshipped exclusively in English.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] By 1891, the percentage of Welsh speakers had fallen to 27.9% and only Lisvane, Llanedeyrn and Creigiau remained as majority Welsh-speaking communities.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The Welsh language became grouped around a small cluster of chapels and churches, the most notable of which is Tabernacl in the city centre, one of four UK churches chosen to hold official services to commemorate the new millennium.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The city's first Welsh-language school (Ysgol Gymraeg Bryntaf) was established in the 1950s.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Aided by Welsh-medium education and migration from other parts of Wales, there are now many more Welsh speakers in the local authority: their numbers doubled between the 1991 and 2021 censuses, from 18,071 (6.6%) to 42,757 (12.2%) residents aged three years and above.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The LSOA (Lower Layer Super Output Area) with the highest percentage of Welsh speakers in the city centre is found in Victoria Park, at 28.7%.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff City Council adopted a five-year Welsh-language strategy in 2017, aimed at increasing the number of Welsh speakers (aged 3+) in Cardiff by 15.9%, from 36,735 in 2011 to 42,584 residents by the 2021 Census.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In the 2021 Census, 42,757 (12.2%) of Cardiff's population could speak Welsh.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In addition to English and Welsh, the diversity of Cardiff's population (including foreign students) means that many other languages are spoken.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] One study has found that Cardiff has speakers of at least 94 languages, with Somali, Urdu, Bengali and Arabic being the most commonly spoken foreign ones.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The modern Cardiff accent is distinct from that of nearby South Wales Valleys.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Due to its diversity and large student population, more people now come to the city to learn English.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Foreign students from Arab states and other European countries are a common sight on the streets of Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The British Council has an office in the city centre and there are six accredited schools in the area.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Since 1922, Cardiff has included Llandaff within its boundary, along with the Anglican Llandaff Cathedral, the parish church of Llandaff and the seat of the Bishop of Llandaff, head of the Church in Wales and the Diocese of Llandaff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] There is a Roman Catholic cathedral in the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Since 1916, Cardiff has been the seat of a Catholic archbishop, but there appears to have been a fall in the estimated Catholic population, with numbers in 2006 around 25,000 fewer than in 1980.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Likewise, the Jewish population appears to have fallen – there are two synagogues in Cardiff, one in Cyncoed and one in Moira Terrace, as opposed to seven at the turn of the 20th century.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] There are several nonconformist chapels, an early 20th century Greek Orthodox church and 11 mosques.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In the 2001 census, 66.9% of Cardiff's population described itself as Christian, a percentage point below the Welsh and UK averages.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The oldest of the non-Christian communities in Wales is Judaism.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Jews were not permitted to live in England and Wales between the 1290 Edict of Expulsion and the 17th century.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] A Welsh Jewish community was re-established in the 18th century.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] There was once a fairly substantial Jewish population in South Wales, most of which has disappeared.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The Orthodox Jewish community congregations are consolidated in the Cardiff United Synagogue in Cyncoed, which was dedicated by Chief Rabbi Jonathan Sacks in 2003.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The Cardiff Reform Synagogue is in Adamsdown.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Built in 1899 as a Welsh Calvinistic Methodist Chapel; a mosque since 1990.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] in Grangetown is the first and largest Hindu temple in Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff's Muslim population is much above the Welsh average and the longest established in the UK, being started by Yemeni and Somali sailors settling in the 19th century.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff now has over 11,000 Muslims with various national affiliations – nearly 52 per cent of the Muslim population in Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The proportion of Cardiff residents declaring themselves Hindu, Sikh and Jewish were all considerably higher than the Welsh averages, but lower than the UK figures.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The city has had a Hindu community since Indian immigrants settled in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The first Hindu temple in the city was opened in Grangetown on 6 April 1979 on the site of an abandoned synagogue.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The 25th anniversary of the founding was celebrated in September 2007 with a parade of over 3,000 people through the city centre, including Hindus from across the United Kingdom and members of Cardiff's other religious communities.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] There are over 2,000 Hindus in Cardiff, worshipping at three temples.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In the 2001 census 18.8% of the city's population stated they had no religion, while 8.6% did not state a religion.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] As the capital city of Wales, Cardiff is the main engine of growth in the Welsh economy.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Though the population of Cardiff is about 10% of the Welsh population, the economy of Cardiff makes up nearly 20% of Welsh GDP and 40% of the city's workforce are daily in-commuters from the surrounding South Wales area.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Industry has played a major part in Cardiff's development for many centuries.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The main catalyst for its transformation from a small town into a big city was the demand for coal required in making iron and later steel, brought to sea by packhorse from Merthyr Tydfil.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] This was first achieved by building a 25-mile (40 km) canal from Merthyr (510 ft or 160 m above sea level) to the Taff Estuary at Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Eventually the Taff Vale Railway replaced the canal barges and massive marshalling yards sprang up as new docks were developed in Cardiff – all prompted by the soaring worldwide demand for coal from the South Wales valleys.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] At its peak, Cardiff's port area, known as Tiger Bay, became the busiest port in the world and – for some time – the world's most important coal port.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In the years leading up to the First World War, more than 10 million tonnes of coal was exported annually from Cardiff Docks.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In 1907, Cardiff's Coal Exchange was the first host to a business deal for a million pounds Sterling.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The high demand for Welsh coal and specifically Welsh artificial fuel, named Patent Fuel, is shown by the numerous factories producing this fuel, with the same recipe, in the region of Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Most well known factories were the Star Patent fuel Co., the Crown Patent fuel, the Cardiff Patent fuel etc.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] After a period of decline, due to low demand on coal, Cardiff's port has started to grow again – over 3 million tonnes of cargo passed through the docks in 2007.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff today is the main finance and business services centre in Wales, with strong representation of finance and business services in the local economy.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] This sector, combined with the public administration, education and health sectors, have accounted for about 75% of Cardiff's economic growth since 1991.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The city was recently placed seventh overall in the top 50 European cities in the fDI 2008 Cities of the Future list published by the fDi magazine, and ranked seventh in terms of attracting foreign investment.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Other major employers include NHS Wales and the Senedd.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] On 1 March 2004, Cardiff was granted Fairtrade City status.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff is one of the most popular tourist destinations in the United Kingdom, receiving 18.3 million visitors in 2010 and generating £852 million for the city's economy.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] One result is that one in five employees in Cardiff are based in the distribution, hotels and restaurants sector, highlighting the growing retail and tourism industries in the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The city has many hotels of varying sizes and standards, providing almost 9,000 available beds.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff is home to the Welsh media and a large media sector with BBC Cymru Wales, S4C and ITV Wales all having studios in the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] There is a large independent TV production industry sector of over 600 companies, employing around 6,000, with a turnover estimated at £350 million.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Just to the north-west of the city, in Rhondda Cynon Taff, the first completely new film studios in the UK for 30 years are being built, to be named Valleywood.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The studios are set to be the biggest in the UK.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] In 2011 the BBC completed the Roath Lock studios in Cardiff Bay to film dramas such as *Casualty*, *Doctor Who*, and *Pobol y Cwm*.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff has several regeneration projects, such as St David's 2 Centre and surrounding areas of the city centre, and the £1.4 billion International Sports Village in Cardiff Bay, which played a part in the London 2012 Olympics.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] It features the only Olympic-standard swimming pool in Wales, the Cardiff International Pool, which opened on 12 January 2008.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] According to the Welsh Rugby Union, the Principality Stadium contributed £1 billion to the Welsh economy in the ten years after it opened in 1999, with around 85% of that staying in the Cardiff area.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Most of Cardiff's shopping portfolio is in the city centre around Queen Street, St Mary Street and High Street, with large suburban retail parks in Cardiff Bay, Culverhouse Cross, Leckwith, Newport Road and Pontprennau, together with markets in the city centre and Splott.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] A £675 million regeneration programme for Cardiff's St.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] David's Centre was completed in 2009, providing a total of 1,400,000 sq ft (130,000 m2) of shopping space, making it one of the largest shopping centres in the United Kingdom.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The centre was named the international shopping centre of the year in 2010 by Retail Leisure International (RLI).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] The Castle Quarter is a commercial area in the north of the city centre, which includes some of Cardiff's Victorian and Edwardian arcades: Castle Arcade, Morgan Arcade and Royal Arcade, and principal shopping streets: St Mary Street, High Street, The Hayes, and Queen Street.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Morgan Arcade is home to Spillers Records, the world's oldest record shop.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p01] Cardiff has a number of markets, including the vast Victorian indoor Cardiff Central Market and the Riverside Community Market.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff Central railway station is the largest railway station in Wales, with eight platforms coping with over 12.5 million passengers a year.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] It provides direct services to Bridgend and Newport, long-distance, cross-Wales services to Wrexham and Holyhead, and services to Bristol, Birmingham, Manchester and London.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff Central Station is situated within the southern border of what was known Temperance Town, a former residential area within central Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff Queen Street railway station is the second busiest in Wales and the hub for the Valley Lines services that connect the South Wales Valleys and the Cardiff suburbs with the city centre.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] It is located at the eastern end of the city centre and provides services to Cardiff Bay.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff has a suburban rail system known as the Valleys & Cardiff Local Routes, operated by Transport for Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] There are eight lines that serve 20 stations in the city, 26 in the wider urban area (including Taffs Well, Penarth and Dinas Powys) and more than 60 in the South Wales valleys and the Vale of Glamorgan.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The South Wales Metro is an integrated public transport system under development in south-east Wales, centered on Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The project is to include the electrification of some of the existing railway lines and the creation of multiple light rail and light rapid transit lines.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Four lines are under construction with a further three planned.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The first lines will link Penarth and Cardiff Bay to Radyr, Treherbert, Aberdare and Merthyr Tydfil, with plans to also serve Pontyclun, St Mellons and Porth Teigr.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Alongside this, current commuter services will be improved with a near-tripling in capacity on some routes to Bridgend and Rhymney.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Domestic and international air links to Cardiff and South & West Wales are provided from Cardiff Airport (CWL), the only international airport in Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The airport lies in the village of Rhoose, 10 miles (16 km) west of the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] There are regular bus services linking the airport with Cardiff city centre, and a train service from Rhoose Cardiff International Airport railway station to Cardiff Central.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The M4 motorway connects Cardiff with Swansea to the west and Newport and London to the east, with four junctions on the M4, including one with the A48(M).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The A470 provides an important link from the city to the Heads of the Valleys road.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] When completed, the A4232 – also known as the Peripheral Distributor Road – will form part of the Cardiff ring-road system, along with the M4 motorway between junctions 30 and 33.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] National Express provides direct services to major cities such as Bristol, London, Newcastle upon Tyne and Manchester.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Most bus services in the city use Cardiff Bus Interchange located next to Central Station, which opened in 2024 replacing an older structure on the same site, whilst intercity and coach services use the coach terminal located near Sophia Gardens in the north of the city centre.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The Taff Trail is a walking and cycle path running for 55 miles (90 km) between Cardiff Bay and Brecon in the Brecon Beacons National Park.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] It runs through Bute Park, Sophia Gardens and many other green areas within Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] It is possible to cycle the entire distance of the Trail almost completely off-road, as it largely follows the River Taff and many of the disused railways of the Glamorganshire valleys.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Nextbike previously operated a public bike-hire scheme in the city between March 2018 and January 2024, with the scheme allegedly being scrapped due to theft.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff Council are seeking a replacement operator.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The Aquabus water taxi runs every hour between the city centre (Taff Mead Embankment) and Cardiff Bay (Mermaid Quay), and between Cardiff Bay and Penarth Cardiff Bay Barrage.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Throughout the year, Cardiff Waterbus sail between the Pierhead on The Waterfront and the Penarth end of the Cardiff Bay Barrage with short sightseeing cruises.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Between March and October boats depart from Cardiff Bay for Flat Holm Island.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The *PS Waverley* and *MV Balmoral* sail from Britannia Quay (in Roath Basin) to various destinations in the Bristol Channel.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Prior to the Big Number Change on 22 April 2000 the area had shorter, six-digit local numbers with an area code of 01222.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] This was 0222 before May 1995, derived from 0 (indicating it was a trunk call), 22 (CA on a telephone pad, for CArdiff) and 2 (as 220 was used for CAmbridge and 221 for BAth).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Before the introduction of automated trunk call dialling, non-local numbers were accessed through a system of manual telephone exchanges, in common with the rest of the United Kingdom.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] There remains a common misconception that local numbers are still six digits long and that the code is 02920, even though there are newer Cardiff numbers in the ranges (029) 21xx xxxx and (029) 22xx xxxx.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff is home to four major institutions of higher education: Cardiff University, Cardiff Metropolitan University, University of South Wales and the Royal Welsh College of Music & Drama.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff University was founded by a royal charter in 1883 as the University College of South Wales and Monmouthshire, is a member of the Russell Group of leading research led universities, having most of its campus in Cathays and the city centre.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff Metropolitan University (formerly UWIC) has campuses in the Llandaff, Cyncoed and city centre areas, and is part of the confederal University of Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The Royal Welsh College of Music & Drama is a conservatoire established in 1949 and is based in the grounds of Cardiff Castle.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The University of South Wales's Cardiff campus, Atrium, is home to the Cardiff School of Creative & Cultural Industries and is located in the city centre.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The total number of higher education students in the city is around 43,900.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The city also has two further education colleges: Cardiff and Vale College and St David's College.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The former is the result of a merger, completed in August 2011, between Coleg Glan Hafren and Barry College.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Further education is also offered at most high schools in the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff has three state nursery schools (one bilingual), 98 state primary schools (two bilingual, fifteen Welsh medium), and 19 state secondary schools (three Welsh medium).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] There is a campaign to build a fourth Welsh medium secondary school in the south of the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] There are also several independent schools in the city, including St John's College, Llandaff Cathedral School, Cardiff Sixth Form College, Kings Monkton School and Howell's School, a single-sex girls' school (until sixth form).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] In 2013 Cardiff Sixth Form College came top of the independent senior schools in the UK, which were based on the percentage of A* and A at Advanced Level.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Also in the top 100 were St John's College and Howell's School.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Notable schools include Whitchurch High School (the largest secondary school in Wales), Fitzalan High School (one of the most multi-cultural state schools in the UK), and Ysgol Gyfun Gymraeg Glantaf (the largest Welsh medium secondary school in Wales).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff is also home to a regional office of the International Baccalaureate Organisation (IBO).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff has many landmark buildings such as the Principality Stadium, Pierhead Building, the Welsh National Museum and the Senedd building, the home of the Welsh Parliament.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff is also known for Cardiff Castle, St David's Hall, St John the Baptist Church, Llandaff Cathedral and the Wales Millennium Centre.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff Castle is a major tourist attraction in the city and is situated in the heart of the city centre.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The National History Museum at St Fagans in Cardiff is a large open-air museum housing dozens of buildings from throughout Welsh history that have been moved to the site in Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The Civic Centre in Cathays Park comprises a collection of Edwardian buildings such as the City Hall, National Museum and Gallery of Wales, Cardiff Crown Court, and buildings forming part of Cardiff University, together with more modern civic buildings.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] These buildings are laid out around the Queen Alexandra Gardens, a formal park which contains the Welsh National War Memorial and a number of other, smaller memorials.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] In addition to Cardiff Castle, Castell Coch is a castle in Tongwynlais, in the north of the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The current castle is an elaborately decorated Victorian folly designed by William Burges for the Marquess and built in the 1870s, as an occasional retreat.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] However, the Victorian castle stands on the footings of a much older medieval castle possibly built by Ifor Bach, a regional baron with links to Cardiff Castle also.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The exterior has become a popular location for film and television productions.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] It rarely fulfilled its intended role as a retreat for the Butes, who seldom stayed there.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] For the Marquess, the pleasure had been in its creation, a pleasure lost following Burges's death in 1881.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff claims the largest concentration of castles of any city in the world.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] As well as Cardiff Castle and Castell Coch, there are the remains of two motte-and-bailey castles in Morganstown and Rhiwbina, known as Morganstown Castle Mound and Twmpath Castle or Twmpath Motte (also known as *Caer Cynwrig*) respectively.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Twmpath (being a Welsh word for a small mound), which along with a castle at Whitchurch (known as Treoda and destroyed by housing in the 1960s) formed an arc of fortifications which divided the Norman lordship from the Welsh lordship of Senghenydd.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Further up the Cefn Cibwr ridge on the boundary with Caerphilly there is also another ruined castle, known as Morgraig Castle (Welsh: *Castell Morgraig*).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Archaeological evidence suggests this castle was never finished, and it is debated whether the fortification was of Norman or Welsh origin.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The concentration of castles indicates the moveable nature of the border between the Norman lordship of Glamorgan, centred at Cardiff, and its Welsh neighbours to the north.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] There is also the ruined Llandaff Bishop's Palace, also known as Llandaff Castle, which was the home of the medieval bishops, which was destroyed about 1403–1404 by the Welsh leader Owain Glyndŵr.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Not strictly a castle in the historical sense, Saint Fagans Castle is a preserved 17th-century manor house, once the seat of the Earls of Plymouth.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Other major tourist attractions are the Cardiff Bay regeneration sites, which include the recently opened Wales Millennium Centre and the Senedd building, and many other cultural and sites of interest, including the Cardiff Bay Barrage and the famous Coal Exchange.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The New Theatre was founded in 1906 and refurbished in the 1980s.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Until the opening of the Wales Millennium Centre in 2004, it was the premier venue in Wales for touring theatre and dance companies.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Other venues popular for concerts and sporting events include Cardiff International Arena, St David's Hall and the Principality Stadium.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff Story, a museum documenting the city's history, has been open to the public since the spring of 2011.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff has over 1,000 listed buildings, ranging from the more prominent buildings such as the castles, to smaller buildings, houses and structures.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cathedral Road was developed by the 3rd Marquis of Bute and is lined by fine villas, some backing on to Sophia Gardens.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff has walks of special interest for tourists and ramblers alike, such as the Centenary Walk, which runs for 2+1⁄4 miles (3.5 km) within Cardiff city centre.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] This route passes through many of Cardiff's landmarks and historic buildings.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The Animal Wall, designed by William Burges in 1866, marks the south edge of Bute Park on Castle Street.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff has many cultural sites varying from the historical Cardiff Castle and out of town Castell Coch to the more modern Wales Millennium Centre and Cardiff Bay.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff was a finalist in the European Capital of Culture 2008.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] In recent years Cardiff has grown in stature as a tourist destination, with recent accolades including Cardiff being voted the eighth favourite UK city by readers of *The Guardian*.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The city was also listed as one of the top 10 destinations in the UK on the official British tourist boards website Visit Britain, and US travel guide Frommers have listed Cardiff as one of 13 top destinations worldwide for 2008.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Annual events in Cardiff that have become regular appearances in Cardiff's calendar include Sparks in the Park, The Great British Cheese Festival, Pride Cymru (formerly Cardiff Mardi Gras), Cardiff Winter Wonderland, Cardiff Festival and Made in Roath.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] A large number of concerts are held in the city, the larger ones at St David's Hall, Cardiff International Arena and occasionally the Principality Stadium.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The annual festival claims to be the UK's largest free outdoor festival, attracting over 250,000 visitors in 2007.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff is unique in Wales in having two permanent stone circles used by the Gorsedd of Bards during Eisteddfodau.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The original circle stands in Gorsedd Gardens in front of the National Museum Cardiff while its 1978 replacement is situated in Bute Park.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Since 1983, Cardiff has hosted the BBC Cardiff Singer of the World competition, a world-renowned event on the opera calendar which is held every two years.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The Wales Millennium Centre hosts performances of opera, ballet, dance, comedy, musicals and is home to the BBC National Orchestra of Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] St David's Hall (which hosts the Singer of the World competition) has regular performances of classical music and ballet as well as music of other genres.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The largest of Cardiff's theatres is the New Theatre, situated in the city centre just off Queen Street.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Other such venues include the Sherman Theatre, Chapter Arts Centre and the Gate Arts Centre.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The Cardiff music scene is established and wide-ranging: home to the BBC National Orchestra of Wales and the Welsh National Opera; has produced several leading acts; has acted as a springboard for Welsh bands to become famous.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Acts hailing from Cardiff include Charlotte Church, Shirley Bassey, Iwan Rheon, the Oppressed, Kids In Glass Houses, Los Campesinos, the Hot Puppies, the School, We're No Heroes, Budgie and Shakin' Stevens.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Also, artists such as Stereophonics, the Automatic, Manic Street Preachers, Lostprophets, Underworld, Super Furry Animals, Catatonia and Bullet for My Valentine have links with the city and are associated with the Cardiff music scene.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] In 2010, Cardiff was named the UK's second "most musical" city by PRS for Music.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff has held a photomarathon in the city each year since 2004, in which photographers compete to take the best 12 pictures of 12 previously unknown topics in 12 hours.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] An exhibition of winners and other entries is held in June/July each year.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff's former municipal baths opened in 1862, as Turkish Baths, and were taken over by the City Council in 1873, before closing over a century later.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] It hosted the 1958 British Empire and Commonwealth Games and was dubbed European City of Sport for its role in international sporting events in 2009 and again in 2014.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The Principality Stadium hosted 11 football matches during the 2012 Summer Olympics, including the opening event and the men's bronze medal match.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Most clubs and bars are situated in the city centre, especially St Mary Street.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] More recently Cardiff Bay has built up a strong night scene, with many modern bars and restaurants.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The Brewery Quarter on St Mary Street is a recently developed venue for bars and restaurant with a central courtyard.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Charles Street is also a popular part of the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff is known for its extensive parks and other green spaces covering around 10% of the city's total area.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] In 2022 according to research by Drinking Straw Cardiff has the highest percentage of green spaces in the UK and the fourth highest in Europe.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Other popular parks include Roath Park in the north, donated to the city by the 3rd Marquess of Bute in 1887, which includes a popular boating lake; Victoria Park, Cardiff's first official park; and Thompson's Park, formerly home to an aviary removed in the 1970s.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Wild open spaces include Howardian Local Nature Reserve, 32 acres (13 ha) of the lower Rhymney valley in Penylan noted for its orchids, and Forest Farm Country Park, over 150 acres (61 ha) along the River Taff in Whitchurch.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff is the Welsh base for the main national broadcasters (BBC Cymru Wales, ITV Wales and S4C).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] A locally based television station, *Made in Cardiff*, is also based in the city centre.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Major filming studios in Cardiff include the BBC's Roath Lock Studios and Pinewood Studios Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The main local newspaper is the *South Wales Echo*; the national paper is the *Western Mail*.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Both are based in Park Street in the city centre.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] *Capital Times*, *Echo Extra* and the South Wales edition of *Metro* are also based and distributed in the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] There are several magazines, including *Primary Times* and a monthly *papur bro*, and a Welsh-language community newsletter called *Y Dinesydd* (The Citizen).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Radio stations serving the city and based in Cardiff include Capital South Wales, Heart South Wales, BBC Radio Wales, BBC Radio Cymru, Nation Radio Wales, Radio Cardiff, Smooth Wales and Xpress Radio.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The Principality Stadium was one of the first six British landmarks to be fully mapped on Google Street View as a 360-degree virtual tour.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff hosts many high-profile sporting events at local, national and international level and in recognition of the city's commitment to sport for all was awarded the title of European Capital of Sport 2014.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Organised sports have been held in the city since the early 19th century.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] National home sporting fixtures are nearly always played in the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] All Wales's multi-sports agencies and many of the country's sports governing bodies have their headquarters in Cardiff and the city's many top quality venues have attracted world-famous sports events, sometimes unrelated to Cardiff or to Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] In 2008/09, 61% of Cardiff residents regularly participated in sport and active recreation, the highest percentage in ll 22 local authorities in Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Rugby union fans around the world have long been familiar with the old National Stadium, Cardiff Arms Park, and its successor the Principality Stadium, which hosted the FA Cup for six years (from 2001 to 2006) it took to rebuild Wembley Stadium.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] In 2009, Cardiff hosted the first Ashes cricket test between England and Australia to be held in Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff hosted eight football matches of the London 2012 Olympics.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] (founded 1899 as Riverside AFC) played their home games at Ninian Park from 1910 until the end of the 2008–09 season.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The club's new home is the Cardiff City Stadium, which they initially rented to the Cardiff Blues, the city's professional rugby union team, the Blues returning to the Arms Park in 2012.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff City have played in the English Football League since the 1920–21 season, climbing to Division 1 after one season.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff City are the only non-English team to have won the FA Cup, beating Arsenal in the 1927 final at Wembley Stadium.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] They were runners up to Portsmouth in the 2008 final, losing 1–0 at the new Wembley Stadium.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] In the 2013/14 and 2018/19 seasons Cardiff City played in the English Premier League.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff Metropolitan University F.C. of the Athletic Union of Cardiff Metropolitan University, based in Cyncoed, play in the Cymru Premier, having been promoted from Welsh League Division One in 2016.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] They were winners of the Welsh League Cup for the 2018–19 season.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff has numerous smaller clubs including Bridgend Street A.F.C., Caerau (Ely) A.F.C., Cardiff Corinthians F.C., Cardiff Draconians F.C., Cardiff Grange Harlequins A.F.C., and Ely Rangers A.F.C., which all play in the Welsh football league system.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] In addition to men's football teams Cardiff City Ladies of the FA Women's Premier League Southern Division are based in the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Teams in the Welsh Premier Women's Football League are Cardiff Met.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Ladies, Cyncoed Ladies and Cardiff City.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] During the 1990s, London-based football club Wimbledon FC expressed interest in relocating to Cardiff, having been without a home of their own since exiting Plough Lane stadium in 1991 and sharing with Crystal Palace FC at Selhurst Park.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The relocation of the club to Cardiff did not happen; in 2003, the club moved to Milton Keynes and a year later rebranded as Milton Keynes Dons.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff Arms Park (Welsh: *Parc yr Arfau Caerdydd*), in central Cardiff, is among the world's most famous venues—being the scene of three Welsh Grand Slams in the 1970s (1971, 1976 and 1978) and six Five Nations titles in nine years—and was the venue for Wales's games in the 1991 Rugby World Cup.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The Arms Park has a sporting history dating back to at least the 1850s, when Cardiff Cricket Club (formed 1819) relocated to the site.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The ground was donated to Cardiff CC in 1867 by the Marquess of Bute.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff Cricket Club shared the ground with Cardiff Rugby Football Club (founded 1876) — forming Cardiff Athletic Club between them — until 1966, when the cricket section moved to Sophia Gardens.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff Athletic Club and the Welsh Rugby Union established two stadia on the site—Cardiff RFC played at their stadium at the northern end of the site, and the Wales national rugby union team played international matches at the National Stadium, Cardiff Arms Park, which opened in 1970.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The National Stadium was replaced by the 74,500 capacity Millennium Stadium (Welsh: *Stadiwm y Mileniwm*) in 1999—in time for the 1999 Rugby World Cup—and is home stadium to the Wales national rugby and football teams for international matches.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] In addition to Wales's Six Nations Championship and other international games, the Principality Stadium held four matches in the 2007 Rugby World Cup and six FA Cup finals (from the 2001–02 to 2005–06 seasons) while Wembley Stadium was being rebuilt.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff Cricket Club was formed in 1819 and Glamorgan County Cricket Club has competed as a first-class county since 1921.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Its headquarters and ground is the SWALEC Stadium, Sophia Gardens, since moving from Cardiff Arms Park in 1966.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The Sophia Gardens stadium underwent multimillion-pound improvements since being selected to host the first "England" v Australia Test match of the 2009 Ashes series.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The Hundred franchise team Welsh Fire is also based at the stadium.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff has a long association with boxing, from 'Peerless' Jim Driscoll — born in Cardiff in 1880 — to more recent, high-profile fights staged in the city.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Frank Bruno heavyweight championship fight at the Arms Park in 1993, and many of Joe Calzaghe's fights, between 2003 and 2007.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff's professional ice hockey team, the Cardiff Devils, plays in the 3,000-seat Ice Arena Wales in the Cardiff International Sports Village.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] It plays in the 12-team professional Elite Ice Hockey League.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Founded in 1986, it was one of the most successful British teams in the 1990s.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff's only American-flag football team is the Hurricanes.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] It won the British Championship in 2014 after falling short by 2 points in a quarter-final to eventual winners, the London Rebels, the previous year.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] It is based at Roath Recreational Ground.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The 1958 Commonwealth Games were hosted by Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] These involved 1,130 athletes from 35 national teams competing in 94 events.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] One of the venues for those Games—The Wales Empire Swimming Pool—was demolished in 1998 to make way for the Principality Stadium.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The GBP32m Cardiff International Pool in Cardiff Bay, opened to the public on 12 January 2008 — part of the GBP1bn International Sports Village (ISV) — is the only Olympic-standard swimming pool in Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Some of the sports facilities at the ISV were to be used as training venues for the London 2012 Olympics.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The Principality Stadium hosts motor-sport events such as the World Rally Championship, as part of Wales Rally GB.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The first indoor special stages of the World Rally Championship were held at the Principality Stadium in September 2005 and have been an annual event since.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The British Speedway Grand Prix, one of the World Championship events, is held at the Principality Stadium.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] While the track—a temporary, purpose built, shale oval—is not universally loved, the venue is considered the best of the World Championship's 11 rounds.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The Cardiff International Sports Stadium, opened 19 January 2009, replacing the Cardiff Athletics Stadium, demolished to make way for the Cardiff City Stadium.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] It has a 4,953 capacity as a multi sport/special event venue, offering certificated international track and field athletics facilities, including an international standard external throws area.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The stadium houses the Headquarters of Welsh Athletics, the sport's governing body for Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The city's indoor track and field athletics sports venue is the National Indoor Athletics Centre, an international athletics and multi sports centre at the University of Wales Institute, Cardiff Campus, Cyncoed.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The Cardiff Half Marathon takes place each October and is one of the largest road races in the United Kingdom, attracting over 20,000 participants and many overseas visitors annually.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The event is organised by the not-for-profit social enterprise Run 4 Wales, and has grown considerably since its establishment in 2003.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] It has hosted the World (2016) Commonwealth (2018) British (2014/2015) and Welsh (Annually) Half Marathon Championships and has held a World Athletics Elite Road Race Label since 2017.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The race is also a part of the SuperHalfs, a series of leading international half marathon races which also includes Lisbon, Prague, Berlin, Valencia and Copenhagen.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Many notable people have hailed from Cardiff, ranging from historical figures such as the 12th-century Welsh leader Ifor Bach to more recent figures such as Roald Dahl, Ken Follett, Griff Rhys Jones, Catrin Dafydd, and the former Blue Peter presenter Gethin Jones.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Also notable is Siân Grigg, BAFTA winner and Oscar nominated Hollywood make-up artist.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] International rugby league players from Cardiff include Frank Whitcombe, Billy Boston, David Willicombe and Colin Dixon.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] International rugby union players include Sam Warburton, Jamie Roberts, Jamie Robinson, Nicky Robinson, Rhys Patchell, and baseball internationals include George Whitcombe and Ted Peterson.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] He was a British Christian monk, bishop, and founder of monasteries and churches.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Reputed to be a cousin, friend, and disciple of Saint David, he was Bishop of Llandaff and founder of the first church at Llandaff Cathedral, where his tomb is.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Cardiff is also well known for its musicians.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Ivor Novello inspired the Ivor Novello Awards.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Idloes Owen, founder of the Welsh National Opera, lived in Llandaff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Dame Shirley Bassey was born and raised in Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Charlotte Church is famous as a crossover classical/pop singer.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Shakin' Stevens was one of the top-selling male artists in the UK during the 1980s.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Tigertailz, a popular glam metal act in the 1980s, also hailed from Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] A number of Cardiff-based bands, such as Catatonia and Super Furry Animals, were popular in the 1990s.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Traumatik, born and raised in Cardiff, gained popularity in the 2010s.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Taff Groves, notably born and raised in Cardiff's Ely and Cathays districts is a former SAS soldier.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] He gained recognition during the 2013 Westgate shopping mall attack in Nairobi, Kenya, where he helped rescue hundreds of civilians while unarmed .
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] In the United States both Cardiff-by-the-Sea in Encinitas, California and Cardiff, Alabama were named after Cardiff in Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] In New Zealand Cardiff, Taranaki was also named after Cardiff in Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] A total of 28 countries have a diplomatic presence in Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] Many of these, such as Germany, Italy, Switzerland, Denmark, Canada, Thailand and the Czech Republic, are represented by honorary consulates.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The United States Embassy to the UK operates a satellite office.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-p02] The following people and military units have received the Freedom of the City of Cardiff; they are listed with the date that they received the honour.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Cardiff University is the only Welsh member of the Russell Group of research-intensive British universities.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Academics and alumni of the university have included four heads of state or government and two Nobel laureates.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] As of 2023, the university's academics include 17 fellows of the Royal Society, 11 fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering, 7 fellows of the British Academy, 21 fellows of the Academy of Medical Sciences and 32 fellows of the Academy of Social Sciences.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The movement began at a meeting in London in 1854 called by Hugh Owen, including leaders of Welsh theological colleges and members of parliament.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] This meeting discussed establishing university colleges in Wales along the same lines as the Queen's Colleges established the previous decade in Ireland, and produced a formal proposal, the "Outline of Constitution for Proposed Welsh Queen's Colleges".
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In August 1880, William Ewart Gladstone's government appointed a departmental committee to conduct "an enquiry into the nature and extent of intermediate and higher education in Wales", chaired by the 1st Baron Aberdare and consisting of Viscount Emlyn, the Reverend Prebendary H.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Robinson, Henry Richard, John Rhys and Lewis Morris.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The committee cited the unique Welsh national identity and noted that many students in Wales could not afford to travel to University in England or Scotland.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] It advocated a national degree-awarding university for Wales, composed of regional colleges, which should be non-sectarian in nature and exclude the teaching of theology.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] After the recommendation was published, Cardiff Corporation sought to secure the location of the college in Cardiff, and on 12 December 1881 formed a University College Committee to aid the matter.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] There was competition to be the site between Swansea and Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] On 12 March 1883, after arbitration, a decision was made in Cardiff's favour.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In April, Lord Aberdare was appointed as the college's first president.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The possible locations considered included Cardiff Arms Park, Cathedral Road, and Moira Terrace, Roath, before the site of the Old Royal Infirmary buildings on Newport Road was chosen.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The University College of South Wales and Monmouthshire opened on 24 October 1883 with courses in biology, chemistry, English, French, German, Greek, history, Latin, mathematics and astronomy, music, Welsh, logic and philosophy, and physics.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] It was incorporated by royal charter the following year; this was the first charter in Wales to allow the enrolment of women and to specifically forbid religious tests for entry.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] John Viriamu Jones was appointed as the college's first principal at the age of 27.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] As the college was not an independent university and could not award its own degrees, it prepared its students for the examinations of the University of London or for further study at Oxford or Cambridge.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] This led to a charter being granted to the University of Wales in 1893, with the colleges becoming members of the new university.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The position of operational head would rotate among heads of the colleges.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In 1885, Aberdare Hall opened as the first hall of residence, allowing women access to the college.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] This moved to its current site in 1895, but remains a single-sex hall.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In 1904 the college appointed the first female associate professor in the UK, Millicent Mackenzie, who in 1910 became the first female full professor at a fully chartered UK university.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In 1901, John Viriamu Jones persuaded Cardiff Corporation to give the college a five-acre site in Cathays Park (instead of selling it as they would have done otherwise).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Soon after, in 1905, work on a new building commenced under the architect W.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Money ran short for the project, however, and although the side-wings were completed in the 1960s the planned great hall was never built.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Caroe sought to combine the charm and elegance of his *alma mater* (Trinity College, Cambridge) with the picturesque balance of many Oxford colleges.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] On 14 October 1909 the "New College" building in Cathays Park (now Main Building) and the "Drapers' Library" (now the Science Library) was opened in a ceremony involving a procession from the "Old College" in Newport Road.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In 1931, the medical school, founded as part of the college in 1893 along with the departments of anatomy, physiology, pathology and pharmacology, was split off to form the Welsh National School of Medicine, renamed the University of Wales College of Medicine in 1984.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The University College of South Wales and Monmouthshire was renamed University College, Cardiff in 1972.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In 1988, University College Cardiff ran into financial difficulties and a declaration of insolvency was considered.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] This led to a merger with the University of Wales Institute of Science and Technology (UWIST) to form the University of Wales College of Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The principal of the new institution was Sir Aubrey Trotman-Dickenson, who had been the principal of UWIST.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] After changes to the constitution in 1996, its name was changed to the University of Wales, Cardiff.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In the early 1990s, the university's computer systems served as the home for The Internet Movie Database.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The college was granted degree-awarding powers by the Privy Council in 1997 although, as a member of the University of Wales, it did not use them at that time.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In 1999, the public name of the university was changed to Cardiff University.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In 2002, ideas were floated to re-merge Cardiff with the University of Wales College of Medicine (UWCM), after the publication of the Welsh Assembly Government's review of higher education in Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] This set in train a series of constitutional reforms.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] On 1 August 2004, Cardiff University ceased to be a member of the University of Wales and became an independent "link institution" affiliated to the federal university.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The process of the merger with UWCM was completed on 1 December 2004, when the Act of Parliament transferring UWCM's assets to Cardiff University received royal assent.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] On 17 December it was announced that the Privy Council had given approval to a new supplemental charter for the keys institution.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] This was sealed on 11 March 2005, granting university status to Cardiff and legally changing the name of the institution to Cardiff University.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Cardiff awarded University of Wales degrees to students admitted before 2005, but has subsequently awarded its own degrees.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In 2005, Wales College of Medicine, as part of the university, launched the North Wales Clinical School in Wrexham, in collaboration with the North East Wales Institute of Higher Education in Wrexham, the University of Wales, Bangor, and the National Health Service in Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] This received funds of £12.5 million from the Welsh Assembly and trebled the number of trainee doctors in clinical training in Wales over a four-year period.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The university also has a Centre for Lifelong Learning, which has been teaching a wide range of courses for over 125 years.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] However, in July 2009, the university announced it was ending over 250 humanities courses at the centre, making over 100 staff redundant.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The university has since reintroduced a number of humanities courses for a trial period beginning in 2010.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In June 2010, the university launched three new research institutes, each offering a new approach to a major modern research issue.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The Neurosciences and Mental Health Research Institute and the Cancer Stem Cell Research Institute are housed in the purpose-built Hadyn Ellis Building and in the Sustainable Places Research Institute.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Another part of the Science and Development Campus, the Cardiff University Brain Research Imaging Centre (CUBRIC), opened in June 2016 for neuroimaging research.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] On 19 February 2018, Malcolm Anderson, a university lecturer committed suicide at age 48 by jumping off a university building.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The inquiry determined that Anderson's suicide was the result of a high-pressure workload.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In 2020, Grace Krause, a PhD student employed at Cardiff University started experiencing headaches and back pain after lengthy work at a computer.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] She tweeted that "Staff are marking hundreds of essays in an impossibly short time.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Stressed, moody, morose, everyone feels like they’re drowning." Soon after, an email from the university was sent to all PhD students asking for these comments to be deleted, in order to avoid negative media attention, which sparked a debate about freedom of speech between employers and employees.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The Arts and Humanities are expected to suffer most severely, with the remaining workforce to be reduced by approximately 120 full-time equivalent positions, which is around half.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The university had around £500 million in unrestricted reserves according to its accounts for 2023–24, which the Universities and Colleges Union said should be partially used to give a longer period for the university's finances to recover.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] However, the university said that "unrestricted reserves" was not the same as cash available to spend.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] It also revealed that the projected deficit for 2024–25, if no action was taken, was £65 million, double the deficit for 2023–24, with the cuts designed to reduce the deficit to £28 million.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In May, the university announced that it would reduce the impact of its cuts by continuing to offer some courses that were previously due to be cancelled, including Nursing, Music, and Modern Languages.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The university also agreed to not make any compulsory redundancies in 2025, following a deal with the UCU to drop plans industrial action in the summer.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The university's deficit is part of the wider financial challenges in the UK higher education sector, where universities are facing budget deficits due to factors such as tuition fee caps, rising operational costs, and fluctuations in student enrolment.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Other institutions, have also announced staff reductions and course closures.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The proposed cuts at Cardiff also led to protests at the Senedd, where the Welsh Government said that there was no more money available for higher education despite universities across Wales suffering financial crises and implementing job cuts and campus closures.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Thomas), which houses the School of Pharmacy and Pharmaceutical Sciences; the law building which houses the Cardiff Law School; and the biosciences building, which provides facilities for both biosciences and medical teaching.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The School of Engineering and School of Physics and Astronomy are located in the Queen's Buildings, off Newport Road, the Schools of Computer Science of Informatics and Mathematics at the Abacws Building, and the School of Journalism, Media and Culture at 2 Central Square.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] A number of university academic facilities are located at the Heath Park campus, based at the University Hospital of Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] This covers the Cardiff University School of Medicine, the School of Dentistry, and the School of Healthcare Sciences.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Most of the university's sports facilities are located at the sports training village in the Talybont Halls complex.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] This includes facilities for football, badminton, basketball, tennis, hockey and gym.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Additional gym facilities and squash courts are located at the university fitness and squash centre, near the city centre campus at Cathays Park.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Extensive playing fields for Rugby, football and lacrosse are located at the university playing fields near Llanrumney.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The university also utilises the nearby Millennium Stadium for rugby fixtures such as the annual varsity tournament.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Cardiff University opened an international branch campus in Astana, the capital city of Kazakhstan, in September 2025.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] This offers four-year bachelor's degree programmes in business and STEM subjects, including a foundation year as standard.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The 26 academic schools of the university are divided into three colleges: Arts, Humanities and Social Sciences; Biomedical and Life Sciences; and Physical Sciences.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Cardiff also has a Doctoral Academy, that brings together the work of four previous discipline-based Graduate Schools and the postgraduate research activity of the university's Graduate Centre.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In the financial year ending 31 July 2024, Cardiff had a total income of £638 million (2022/23 – £627.2 million) and total expenditure of £500.4 million (2022/23 – £603 million).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] At year end, Cardiff had endowments of £53.1 million (2023 – £46.2 million) and total net assets of £852.6 million (2023 – £679 million).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Cardiff University is a highly renowned for several subjects in its department.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Cardiff has produced two Nobel Laureates on its staff, Sir Martin Evans and Robert Huber.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In 2013, Cardiff University was ranked as one of the best UK universities for supporting LGBT students, by the charity Stonewall in its annual *Gay by Degree* guide.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The university was one of only two in the UK and the only one in Wales to achieve top marks in a Stonewall checklist of priorities for LGBT+ students.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Cardiff University was ranked joint 168th in Best Global Universities by US News in 2021.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] It was ranked 164th among universities around the world by SCImago Institutions Rankings in 2021.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The Round University Rankings ranked Cardiff University 162nd globally in 2021.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The Center for World University Rankings listed Cardiff University 159th in the world in 2021.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] According to QS World University Rankings by Subject in 2021, Cardiff University ranked within the world's top 50 universities in communication and media studies (28), in Architecture and Built environment (37) and Psychology (59).
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Other subjects ranked within the top 100 are dentistry, and mineral and mining engineering (49) civil and structural engineering, geography, social policy and administration, pharmacy and pharmacology, English language and literature, and sociology.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In the 2024/25 academic year, the student body consisted of 31,505 students, composed of 24,645 undergraduates and 6,860 postgraduate students.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Based on 2022/23 HESA entry standards data published in domestic league tables, which include a broad range of qualifications beyond the top three exam grades, the average student at Cardiff University achieved 152 points.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] According to the 2017 *Times* and *Sunday Times* Good University Guide, approximately 15 per cent of Cardiff's undergraduates come from independent schools.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In the 2016–2017 academic year, the university had a domicile breakdown of 76:5:19 of UK:EU:non-EU students respectively with a female to male ratio of 59:41.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The university maintains 15 student halls and a number of student houses throughout the city of Cardiff; providing a total of 5,362 student places in accommodation.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] They are in a variety of architectural styles and ages, from the Gothic Aberdare Hall, built in 1895, to the modern Talybont Gate Building, completed in 2014.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] All first-year students are guaranteed a place in university owned and managed halls.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The Cardiff University Students' Union is a student-run organisation aiming to promote student interests within the university and further afield.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The Cardiff University Students' Union building is near Cathays Park, next to Cathays railway station.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] It has shops, a night club and the studios of Xpress Radio and Gair Rhydd, the student newspaper.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] It is democratically controlled by the student body through the election of seven full-time officers, who manage the running of the Union.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The Union provides a range of services, including a number of cafes, bars and shops, as well as advice, training and representation.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The Union is an affiliated member of the National Union of Students.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The students' union supports over 200 societies across a wide range of interests as well as 70 sports clubs through the athletic union.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Xpress Radio is the student radio station.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] It broadcasts daily during term from studios in the Students' Union building, with programming such as comedy panel shows, new music showcases, local music showcases, and film reviews.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Student activism at Cardiff University has included protests about the university's investments in arms companies in 2009, as part of a larger student movement in the UK at that time, and participating in the 2024 pro-Palestinian protests on university campuses.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The encampment dispersed on 17 July 2024 after the university confirmed that it already met some demands and committed to address some of the others.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The following year, in May 2025, Cardiff University Students' Union released a statement acknowledging a new pro-Palestinian encampment on campus.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The university was also granted precautionary injunctive relief for a year to prevent occupation of fourteen university buildings.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The university stated that this action "could be interpreted as curtailing the right to protest and freedom of speech, but this is not the case. ...
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] This decision is about ensuring the safety of everyone in our University community".
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Caerdydd Students for Palestine responded that "Cardiff University would rather violently repress its students than speak to us.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The Cardiff University Athletic Union is the body that supports student sport at Cardiff, it oversees more than 60 competitive and non-competitive sports clubs, many of which compete in the British Universities and Colleges Sport league.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The university's Ice Hockey team, the Cardiff Redhawks (which also recruits players from other Welsh universities) competes in the British Universities Ice Hockey Association leagues.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The university's sports teams also take part in the annual Welsh Varsity against Swansea University, which includes the Welsh Boat Race, and several other sporting competitions.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The Welsh Varsity rugby match has been described as "probably... the second biggest Varsity Game next to Oxford vs Cambridge".
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Cardiff participates in British Universities and Colleges Sport which manages a sporting framework of competitive fixtures and events for over 150 institutions around the UK.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Cardiff registers nearly 100 teams in the various leagues and competitions each year and sees students travelling around the country to represent Cardiff University.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] In 2013 Cardiff team achieved 15th position overall across the 50 different sports hosting events.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Cardiff University's motto is *Gwirionedd, Undod a Chytgord*.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The Welsh motto translates as *Truth, Unity and Concord* or *Truth, Unity and Harmony*.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] It is taken from the prayer for the Church militant as it appears in the 1662 *Book of Common Prayer*.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Cardiff University's current coat of arms was granted by the College of Arms in 1988 following the merger of University College Cardiff and the University of Wales Institute of Science and Technology.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The coat of arms incorporates features from the heraldry of both former institutions.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The three chevrons are derived from the arms of the de Clare lords of Glamorgan.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The open book signifies learning; on it are the crescent and annulet, marks of cadence that indicate that University College Cardiff was the second of the University of Wales' institutions, and that the University of Wales Institute of Science and Technology was the fifth.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] A notable feature of the arms are the supporters, which in heraldry are rarely granted to universities.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The supporters are an angel from University College Cardiff and a Welsh Dragon from the University of Wales Institute of Science and Technology.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] The crest is a Welsh dragon in the stance of a lion; it stands on the helmet.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/cardiff-university] Both the dragon and the helmet are distinguished by being front-facing rather than in profile as is more usually found in Welsh heraldry.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Jones served in the Cabinet as Secretary for Agriculture and Rural Development in the Welsh Government from 2000 to 2002, and as Minister of State for the Environment from 2003 to 2007.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Following the 2007 election, he was appointed Minister for Education, Culture and the Welsh Language, and thereafter Counsel General for Wales and Leader of the House following the One Wales coalition agreement with Plaid Cymru.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Jones succeeded Rhodri Morgan as first minister and the leader of Welsh Labour on 1 December 2009.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] The third politician to lead the Welsh Government, Jones was formally nominated as first minister by the National Assembly on 9 December 2009, and was sworn into office the following day.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] In April 2018 he announced he would step down as first minister that autumn, and in December 2018 Mark Drakeford (the Finance Secretary in Jones' cabinet) was elected as his replacement.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Born in Swansea, he was raised in Bridgend in a Welsh-speaking family, and is a fluent speaker of Welsh.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] He was a pupil at Brynteg Comprehensive School in Bridgend, and then graduated at the University of Wales, Aberystwyth with a LLB degree in 1988, where he joined the Labour Party during the miners' strike of 1984–1985.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Carwyn Jones graduated in 1988 from the University College of Wales, Aberystwyth with a Bachelor of Laws degree and went on to the Inns of Court School of Law in London to train as a barrister.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] He was called to the Bar at Gray's Inn in 1989 and subsequently spent a further year in Cardiff in pupillage followed by ten years in practice at Gower Chambers, Swansea, in family, criminal and personal injury law.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] He left practice to become a tutor at Cardiff University for two years on the Bar Vocational Course.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Jones was a County Borough Councillor for Bridgend for five years, where he eventually chaired the Labour group.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] He became a Member of the National Assembly for Wales for Bridgend in 1999 and was appointed Deputy Secretary in the National Assembly for Wales on 23 February 2000.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] On 23 July 2000, he was appointed to the Cabinet as Secretary for Agriculture and Rural Development in the Welsh Government, before the title was changed to Minister in October 2000.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] His responsibilities in this role included the environment, countryside issues, town and country planning, sustainable development, agriculture and rural development.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] In June 2002, his brief was expanded when he was appointed Minister for Open Government in addition to his other duties.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] During this time, he was responsible for the Welsh response to the 2001 foot-and-mouth disease outbreak.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] After the 2007 election, he was appointed Minister for Education, Culture and the Welsh Language, responsible for the Department for Education, Lifelong Learning and Skills and the culture, Welsh language and sport portfolios.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] After his party entered into coalition with Plaid Cymru, Jones was appointed as Counsel General for Wales and Leader of the House.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Following the announcement by the Welsh Labour Leader and First Minister Rhodri Morgan in September 2009 that he would be resigning both posts in December 2009, Jones entered the subsequent election to become his successor, where his opponents were Edwina Hart and Huw Lewis.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] On 1 December 2009, Jones was elected the new Leader with over 50% of the vote.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] After winning the leadership election in 2009, Jones was confirmed as the third First Minister of Wales on 9 December 2009.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Jones was formally sworn into office as First Minister the following day.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] After the defeat of the Labour Party in the 2010 United Kingdom general election, and the resignation of Gordon Brown as Prime Minister, Jones was the most senior Labour elected representative and government minister in the United Kingdom.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] He was appointed a Privy Counsellor on 9 June 2010.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Following the 2011 elections to the Welsh Assembly, Labour increased its number of seats to just one under the amount needed for a majority.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Jones opted to form a minority government as opposed to continuing the coalition, allowing Labour to govern alone.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Following the UK Coalition Government's austerity programme, some members of the UK cabinet sought to criticise Jones.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] On 8 September 2012, in defending the UK government spending cuts, Deputy Prime Minister Nick Clegg accused Jones of blaming London.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] A spokesman for Jones responded, "We've again witnessed another graceless visit to Wales by Nick Clegg.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] People would be right to ask themselves – why does he bother coming to Wales, if all he wants to do is hurl insults about issues that he's clearly very poorly briefed on?
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] The fact is, the Welsh Government is utterly focused on making up for the failure of the UK Government to stimulate adequate and sustainable growth to enable Welsh companies to survive and expand during these extremely difficult times.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Business leaders right across Wales are telling us they need much more support from the UK Government.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] So they'll be scratching their heads at the incoherence of the Deputy Prime Minister's message and the paucity of ideas emanating from the UK Government.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] On 28 February 2012, Jones told the Welsh Assembly, "We would like to see many routes emerging from Cardiff Airport, but the airport must get its act together...
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Last week, I went to the airport and the main entrance was shut.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] People could not go in through the main entrance; they had to go through the side entrance.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] On 20 March 2012, Jones again attacked Cardiff Airport saying "business people" had complained to him "week after week, for many months about the airport".
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] He asserted he had put their points to the owners of the airport but "they have been met with a shrug of the shoulders.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] On 27 June 2012, the Task Force, comprising tourist chiefs, local government spokesmen and trade unionists, met for the first time.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] A bid to obtain the full minutes of the meeting under the Freedom of Information Act 2000 was refused by the Information Commissioner.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] In 2013, Jones came out against Scottish independence in the September 2014 referendum.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Following the 2016 National Assembly for Wales election, the Labour Party was two seats short of an overall majority in the Assembly and Jones began negotiations with opposition parties to keep his party in power.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Both Carwyn Jones and Leanne Wood were nominated for the position of First Minister.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] This vote followed discussions held by Plaid AM Adam Price with both The Welsh Conservatives and UKIP.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Adam Price later told The Western Mail's Martin Shipton that the Conservatives were "not exactly enamoured by the prospect of electing Leanne as First Minister with no offer of a place in government.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] In a vote on 11 May 2016 both Jones and Wood tied on 29 votes each in the vote to elect a First Minister.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Under the Government of Wales Act 2006, if a First Minister is not elected within 28 days of the Assembly elections, those elections would need to be repeated.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Following negotiations with the Plaid Cymru leader, a second vote on 18 May saw an unopposed Jones re-elected as First Minister, enabling him to begin the process of forming a minority government.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] He was sworn in as First Minister on 19 May, after which he said that he was "delighted to introduce the team who will be taking Wales forward over the next five years".
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Among his appointments was the former Welsh Liberal Democrat leader Kirsty Williams, who became Wales's Education Secretary.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Following the death of the Welsh Assembly Member Carl Sargeant, some had called for Jones to resign as First Minister.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Allegations of inappropriate sexual touching had been reported against Sargeant, prompting Jones to remove him from his cabinet position.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Later, Sargeant was found dead at his home as a result of suspected suicide.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Critics considered it unfair that Sargeant seemingly had not been told details of the allegations and therefore was not put in a position to respond to them adequately.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] He returned to the media spotlight in April 2018 when he was cleared by independent investigator James Hamilton of accusations that he had misled the Assembly about bullying problems in the Government which were first alleged in 2014, and which Jones in 2017 told the Assembly had been resolved.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Shortly after the completion of the investigation, on 21 April 2018, Jones announced that he would stand down as First Minister in the autumn.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] In May 2018, Jones announced he would leave the Welsh Assembly at the next Assembly election in 2021.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Following the election of Mark Drakeford as Leader of Welsh Labour, on 6 December 2018, Jones tendered his resignation as First Minister to the Queen on 12 December 2018, and was succeeded by Drakeford as First Minister the following day.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] He remained a Member of the Senedd for Bridgend as previously indicated until the 2021 Senedd election.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] In 2019, he was subject to further press coverage when discussion emerged around the evidence given by Jones during the inquest into the death of Sargeant.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] The coroner, John Gittins, confirmed that Jones had given a statement as evidence, but that Jones had later withdrawn a particular remark regarding his actions upon hearing of Sargeant's death.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Gittins stated that Jones was either mistaken, or more controversially, "perhaps deliberately" misleading about the facts he had originally stated.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Gittins later accepted in his judgment that Jones had acted "perfectly properly".During the inquest Jones had also sought to have evidence admitted pertaining to Sargeant; however, this had been rejected by Gittins.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Jones later appealed against the decision but this was rejected in the High Court.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Since stepping down from the leadership, Jones has participated in a number of public discussions on a range of Welsh civic issues.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] These have included the debating of Welsh independence, including one event at the National Eisteddfod in which he conceded that Wales was "not too poor to be independent".
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] He has, however, continued to argue for greater devolution rather than independence, arguing that independence is "not as easy as some think".
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Jones was announced as a senior contributor to the non-political "business to business news platform" Business News Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] He has launched a podcast series with the website entitled "Carwyn Meets", where he has interviewed the Welsh Rugby Union CEO Roger Lewis, the Economy, Infrastructure and Skills Minister Ken Skates, the Celtic Manor Resort CEO Ian Edwards, and the Transport for Wales' CEO James Price, among others.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] It was announced on 15 January 2020 that Jones had been appointed as Professor of Law at Aberystwyth University, and would work in the law and criminology department on a part-time basis.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] In November 2020, Jones was elected as the representative of Welsh Labour on the Labour party's national executive committee.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] In May 2021, Jones was announced as the Chair of Trustees for the Welsh Climate Charity, Size of Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] In late 2024, Jones was nominated for a Labour Party life peerage by Prime Minister Keir Starmer.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] He was created *Baron Jones of Penybont, of Penybont in the County of Penybont Ar Ogwr*, on 23 January 2025, and was introduced to the House of Lords on 27 January.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/carwyn-jones] Jones met his wife Lisa, who is from Belfast, while they both studied at Aberystwyth University.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales] The **Noah's Ark Children's Hospital for Wales** (Welsh: *Ysbyty Arch Noa Plant Cymru*) is a children's hospital in Cardiff, Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales] It is situated on the site of the University Hospital of Wales in the Heath area of the city and is managed by the Cardiff and Vale University Health Board.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales] The first phase of the hospital was financed by from funds raised by the Noah's Ark Appeal, which had been founded in May 2000, together with some support from the Welsh Assembly Government.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales] The appeal patrons included Dame Shirley Bassey, who was born in Cardiff, Charlotte Church and Catherine Zeta-Jones.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales] The first phase, which was designed by Boyes Rees and built by Laing O'Rourke at a cost of £10 million, was officially opened by Catherine Zeta-Jones and Michael Douglas in June 2006.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales] In November 2007 Edwina Hart AM, the Health Minister of Wales, announced that the Welsh Assembly Government would fund that part of the capital costs for the second phase of the hospital which was not already being financed by the three local health boards and Health Commission Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales] In June 2010 the playrooms at the hospital were restocked with new toys by city department store John Lewis after the South Wales Echo reported that the theft of toys threatened a playroom with closure.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales] Zeta-Jones and Douglas returned to the hospital to celebrate the 10th anniversary of the launch of the fundraising campaign in July 2010.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales] Zeta-Jones announced in November 2012 that the hospital would become known as the Noah's Ark Children's Hospital for Wales.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales] The second phase of the hospital, which was designed by Boyes Rees and built by Interserve at a cost of £64 million, was opened by First Minister Carwyn Jones in May 2015.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales] New facilities included five operating theatres, the new paediatric intensive care unit, a new hydrotherapy pool, and an "open" MRI scanner.
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales] The Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health, as well as doctors at the hospital, have described the new facilities as "world class".
[src:noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales/noah-s-ark-children-s-hospital-for-wales] In 2017, a play garden also opened in the second phase building.
